We must “build” the accounts payable (AP) balance by adding up the amounts from purchase transactions that were recorded as “Unpaid” with the payment method “Account Payable.” (Typically the opening balance – any “Initial” transactions – does not include AP.) 

Step‐by‐step, we check each row:

1. The three “Initial20231231001” rows are for cash, bank, and fixed assets. They do not affect AP so the AP opening balance is 0.00.

2. Look for “Purchase” transactions that use “Account Payable” as the payment method and have a status of “Unpaid”. In our table these are:

 • Row “Purchase20231231001”: Amount = 809280.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231002”: Amount = 19650.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231005”: Amount = 44850.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231006”: Amount = 605000.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231007”: Amount = 75250.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231012”: Amount = 100800.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231013”: Amount = 596000.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231015”: Amount = 1470000.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231016”: Amount = 700000.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231017”: Amount = 218240.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231018”: Amount = 399000.0  
 • Row “Purchase20231231020”: Amount = 558000.0  

3. Adding these amounts:

 809280.0  
+ 19650.0    = 828930.0  
+ 44850.0    = 873780.0  
+ 605000.0   = 1478780.0  
+ 75250.0    = 1554030.0  
+ 100800.0   = 1654830.0  
+ 596000.0   = 2250830.0  
+ 1470000.0  = 3720830.0  
+ 700000.0   = 4420830.0  
+ 218240.0   = 4639070.0  
+ 399000.0   = 5038070.0  
+ 558000.0   = 5596070.0  

Thus the ending AP balance is 5,596,070.0.

So, in our answer the AP initial value is “0.00” and the AP ending balance is “5596070.00.”
